image_info: L1 rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis in unstained wet mounts of stool. Note the short buccal canal and the genital primordium (red arrow).
L2 rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis in unstained wet mounts of stool. Note the short buccal canal and the genital primordium (red arrows), but longer intestinal tract than seen in an L1.

Close-up of the anterior end of a rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis, showing the short buccal canal (red arrow) and the bulbar portion of the rhabditoid esophagus, also called the median bulb (blue arrow). Image taken at 1000x oil magnification.
Rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis in an unstained wet mount of stool. Note the short buccal canal and the genital primordium (red arrow).
Rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis in an unstained wet mount of stool. Note the esophageal bulb (blue arrow) and prominent genital primordium (red arrow).
Rhabditiform larva of S. stercoralis in an unstained wet mount of stool. Note the prominent genital primordium (blue arrow), esophageal bulb (red arrow) and short buccal canal (green arrow).
Filariform (L3) larva of S. stercoralis in an unstained wet mount.
Autoinfective (L4) larva of S. stercoralis in a sputum specimen, stained with Giemsa. Image taken at 200x magnification.
Higher magnification (1000x oil) of the L4 larva in Figure B. Note the notched tail.
Free-living adult male S. stercoralis. Note the presence of the spicule (red arrow).
Free living adult male S. stercoralis, showing a spicule (red arrow). A smaller, rhabditiform larva lies adjacent to the adult male.
Adult free-living female S. stercoralis alongside a smaller rhabditiform larva. Note the developing eggs in the adult female.
Adult free-living female S. stercoralis. Note the row of eggs within the femaleâ€™s body.
Parasitic adult female of S. stercoralis.
Another field showing a parasitic female (black arrow), rhabditiform larvae (darts), and a cluster of eggs (white arrow).
A cluster of eggs from the same stool specimen. Note the rhabditiform larvae within.
Cross-sections of adult parasitic female S. stercoralis (blue arrows) in small intestine tissue, stained with H&E. Image taken at 200x magnification.

Sections of S. stercoralis from a duodenal biopsy specimen, stained with H&E. Although strongyloidiasis could not be confirmed based on microscopy alone, this case was confirmed using molecular methods (PCR). Image taken at 200x magnification.
Higher magnification (1000x oil) of an adult parasitic female of S. stercoralis from the same specimen as Figure A. Note the intestine (red arrow) and ovaries (blue arrows).

Higher magnification (1000x oil) of a gravid adult parasitic female of S. stercoralis from the same specimen as Figure A. Note the intestine (blue arrow), ovary (red arrow) and an egg within the uterus (green arrow).

Cross-sections of S. stercoralis larvae in an intestinal biopsy specimen, stained with H&E. Image taken at 1000x oil magnification. The patient developed strongyloidiasis following transplant of an infected kidney.
Longitudinal-section of a larva of S. stercoralis from the same specimen as Figure E. Image taken at 400x magnification.
S. fuelleborni subsp. fuelleborni egg from the feces of a naturally-infected primate, iodine stained. Note the rhabditiform larva in an early, cleaved, stage of development.
S. fuelleborni subsp. fuelleborni egg from the feces of a naturally-infected primate.
S. fuelleborni subsp. fuelleborni egg from the feces of a naturally-infected primate).
